    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Investigating Orange Slices</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_qdcr1l6q">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_5nzthl9y">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_brguqpvq">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_dlr69jkq">
                    Work in groups of 2–3
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_uprn7u8h">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rlbcl8ko">
                    Organise learners into groups of 2–3. Demonstrate safe cutting technique or provide pre-cut oranges for safety. Guide learners to identify the two radii: inner (juice sac boundary) and outer (peel edge). Encourage accurate measurement using rulers. Ask: <q>What shape is the edible part of the orange slice?</q> Probe: <q>Why do we subtract the inner area from the outer area?</q> Learners should discover: annulus area = outer circle area − inner circle area.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_tfr49r3i">
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_ctq4lmyj">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_qy19clik"><p xml:id="auto_r2dk694x">What shape is the edible part of the orange slice?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_0l9trt1i"><p xml:id="auto_jouwoipy">Why do we subtract the inner circle area from the outer circle area?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_h9ripi7b"><p xml:id="auto_i6ilwnuq">How do your calculated areas compare across different slices?</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_chvdr7mk"><p xml:id="auto_b7ufcofd">What real-life objects have a similar ring shape?</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>


    <activity xml:id="auto_3nxtovqb">
        <statement>
               <p xml:id="auto_qp3ouewr">
                 <alert> Work in Groups</alert>
              </p>
               <p xml:id="auto_p62fppws">
                  <alert>What you need</alert>
              </p>
               <p xml:id="auto_saql2538">
                  <ul>
                      <li xml:id="auto_ljotit9v">
                          <p xml:id="auto_01gh6wp4">
                             An orange and a knife.
                         </p>
                     </li>
                 </ul>
              </p>
              <p xml:id="auto_88vzpmad">
                  <ul>
                      <li xml:id="auto_5ty7zt1v">
                          <p xml:id="auto_9cghv4pn">
                             A ruler, a pen and a book to record your measurements.
                          </p>
                      </li>
                 </ul>
              </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_uvgxhrpp">
                      <ul>
                         <li xml:id="auto_p2a5m6kk">
                              <p xml:id="auto_hz7mh6bw">
                                 A plate.
                              </p>
                         </li>
                     </ul>
                </p>
                   <p xml:id="auto_xxbbta9p">
                     <alert>What to do</alert>
                  </p>
                     <p xml:id="auto_ullf37cg">
                         <ul>
                              <li xml:id="auto_06lbpiq7">
                                  <p xml:id="auto_p7dt2c2l">
                                     Cut the orange into two equal halves, crossectionally, to obtain an image like the one shown.
                                  </p>
                                  <image source="orangeimage.jpg">
                                    <shortdescription>Image showing a crossectional cut of an orange,.</shortdescription>
                                </image>
                              </li>
                              <li xml:id="auto_c50ttoqh">
                                   <p xml:id="auto_mi584uky">
                                     From the crossectional cuts, slice them crossectionally to obtain 5 slices of the orange, each slice being a part of a circle.
                                  </p>
                              </li>
                              <li xml:id="auto_7nj1cpl0">
                                  <p xml:id="auto_ocon28n1">
                                     Take a slice, measure the internal (the radius from the center to where the juice sac ends) and external (radius from the center to the exocarp) radius of the slices using a ruler and record the measurement.
                                  </p>
                              </li>
                              <li xml:id="auto_ux3mk1os">
                                  <p xml:id="auto_g5g620qa">
                                     Repeat the whole process for the other slices.
                                  </p>
                              </li>
                                  <li xml:id="auto_wtxyetk4">
                                      <p xml:id="auto_sdm3hzat">
                                         From the measurements you have recorded, calculate the area of each annulus.
                                      </p>
                                  </li>
                                     <li xml:id="auto_w3ct30aj">
                                          <p xml:id="auto_0418h74y">
                                             Using the formula : 
                                              <md>
                                                 <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
                                                 <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
                                                 <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow>
                                              </md>
                                          </p>
                                      </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_3xf7g2yi">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_aannwrvm">
                                            Share your results with your classmates and compare your answers.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                         </ul>
                     </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
     <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_0sty7pky">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_71nhs16o">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_51f73gv7">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_vjpgydyq">
                    To formalise the key formulas for sectors, annuli, and segments and address common challenges revealed during the anchor activity.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_09itvfxa">
                <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_jruxj2lr">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7328gujy"><p xml:id="auto_csa5xo1f">Emphasise visual identification: sector = pie slice, annulus = ring, segment = chord region.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_t3v1tcjt"><p xml:id="auto_uj5cfmw7">Use diagrams to show which formula applies to which shape.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_qv6pojpg"><p xml:id="auto_i18pe3m9">Connect formulas to subtraction logic (annulus and segment both involve subtraction).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_k9b0g7v5"><p xml:id="auto_qq92a0eb">Provide a formula reference chart for quick lookup.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_j4uydsa0"><p xml:id="auto_umekhujm">Use real objects (pizza, washer, orange) to reinforce concepts.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight xml:id="auto_wr9s4dmx">
        <p xml:id="auto_0vbvp0uw">
            <em><term> Area of part of a circle</term></em> refers to calculating the area of sectors, segments, or annuli. Real-life applications include:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m26xask7"><ol marker="(1)">
            <li xml:id="auto_twlgdu5d">
                <p xml:id="auto_cnmzk44c">
                    Bakers: Calculate pizza slice area to determine portion sizes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_uhj7gaeq">
                <p xml:id="auto_j7qclrfx">
                    Pastry chefs: Calculate cake slice area for serving
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_b546wirr">
                <p xml:id="auto_tqcdb7nm">
                    Fruit sellers: Calculate orange or watermelon slice area for pricing
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_gij5ql6e">
                <p xml:id="auto_j52mq952">
                    Engineers: Design washers, gears, and mechanical parts
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_6759tfvm">
                <p xml:id="auto_148jws4a">
                    Telecommunications: Model overlapping signal coverage areas
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
        <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Shape</cell>
                <cell>Formula</cell>
                <cell>Real-Life Example</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Sector</cell>
                <cell><m>A = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m></cell>
                <cell>Pizza slice, cake slice</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Annulus</cell>
                <cell><m>A = \pi (R^2 - r^2)</m></cell>.
                <cell>Washer, orange slice, ring</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Segment</cell>
                <cell><m>A = A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle}</m></cell>
                <cell>Signal overlap, window design</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Sector: Pizza Slicing</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_b28pea8a">
            A sector is a "pie-shaped" region bounded by two radii and an arc. When a pizza is sliced into equal pieces, each slice is a sector
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_akg73j8p">
            Formula: <m>A_\text{sector} = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_jx1gf86j">
            Where <m>\theta</m> is the central angle in degrees and <m>r</m> is the radius.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_3afljimo">
            <alert>Key insight:</alert> The fraction <m>\frac{\theta}{360}</m> represents what portion of the full circle the sector occupies.
        </p>
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
         <title>Annulus: Metal Washers and Orange Slices</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_c8887xcj">
            An annulus is a ring-shaped region between two concentric circles (circles with the same center).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gfh9x7tg">
            Formula: <m>A_\text{annulus} = \pi(R^2 - r^2) = \pi R^2 - \pi r^2</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o38k4nng">
            Where <m>R</m> is the outer radius and <m>r</m> is the inner radius.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_sr67iwav">
            <alert>Key insight:</alert> Subtract the inner "hole" area from the outer circle area to get the ring area.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_5mykncsh">
            <alert>Applications:</alert> Metal washers distribute load in bolts/nuts; orange slices have edible ring between juice sac and peel.
        </p>
        
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Segment: Signal Coverage Overlap</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qq73qg2i">
            A segment is a region bounded by a chord and an arc. It is calculated by subtracting the triangle area from the sector area.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_siufci7m">
            Formula: <m>A_\text{segment} = A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_z66dd17y">
            Where <m>A_\text{sector} = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m> and <m>A_\text{triangle} = \frac{1}{2}r^2\sin(\theta)</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_fuyps1aw">
            <alert>Key insight:</alert> The segment is the "leftover" area after removing the triangle from the sector.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o4i34q50">
            <alert>Applications:</alert> Overlapping signal ranges from towers, architectural window designs.
        </p>
        
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Choosing the Right Formula</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_n1yemv9m">
            Sector: When the region is bounded by two radii and an arc (pizza slice, cake slice)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_vxxyfoks">
            Annulus: When the region is a ring between two circles (washer, orange slice)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mpweiqti">
            Segment: When the region is bounded by a chord and an arc (signal overlap, window)
        </p>
     
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_ljiz67qt">
            <alert>Address common challenges revealed during the anchor activity:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xqictca3">
            Emphasize visual identification: sector = pie slice, annulus = ring, segment = chord region
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_62w58b2p">
            Use diagrams to show which formula applies to which shape
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_h8d9dbmv">
            Connect formulas to subtraction logic (annulus and segment both involve subtraction)
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_feoj4acf">
            Provide formula reference chart for quick lookup
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_58vwmt5b">
            Use real objects (pizza, washer, orange) to reinforce concepts
        </p>
        
    </paragraphs>
       
        
    

    </insight>

