          <p xml:id="auto_mbm56ucu">
             <em><term> Area of part of a circle</term></em> refers to calculating the area of a sector, segment or annulus.
             This is important in real-life because it can be used to calculate the area of a slice of pizza by a baker,
             the area of a slice of cake by a pastry chef, the area of a slice of orange by a fruit seller, 
             the area of a slice of watermelon by a farmer and many more.
          </p>
           <p xml:id="auto_wpjlnkmm">
             Some of the real life applications of calculating the area of a part of a circle include:
           </p>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_w3kz578s">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_xmz51wvj">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_gbp6tzd8">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_o3ks46ox">
                    To apply sector, annulus, and segment formulas to real-world problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_j8nuh4rn">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_a1s8c8ps">
                    Guide learners through the worked examples. For each example, ask learners to first identify the shape (sector, annulus, or segment), then select the correct formula, and finally substitute and compute. After worked examples, assign individual practice problems and circulate to provide support.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <paragraphs>
        <title> Slicing a pizza</title>
             <image source="pizza-image.jpg">
                  <shortdescription> image showing a pizza sliced into 8 pieces.</shortdescription>
            </image>
           <p xml:id="auto_zy9vzom0">
             One of the most common applications of calculating the area of a part of a circle is slicing a pizza.
             A pizza is usually sliced into equal pieces, and the area of each slice can be calculated using the formula for the area of a sector.
             This helps in determining how much pizza each person gets and can also be used to calculate the total area of the pizza.
           </p>
           <example xml:id="auto_0wggbftr">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_zcrphc6b">
                    A pizza has a radius of <m>12</m> inches and is sliced into 8 equal pieces. Calculate the area of each slice of pizza.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_60grko0h">
                    To calculate the area of each slice of pizza, we can use the formula for the area of a sector:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    where <m>\theta</m> is the central angle of the sector and <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle.
                    Since the pizza is sliced into 8 equal pieces, each slice corresponds to a central angle of <m>\theta = \frac{360}{8} = 45^\circ</m>.
                    The radius of the pizza is given as <m>r = 12</m> inches.
                    Substituting these values into the formula, we get:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{45}{360} \times \pi (12)^2 </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{8} \times \pi (144) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 18\times \frac{22}{7} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 56.57 \text{in}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
           </example>
            
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Designing a metal washer</title>
                 <image source="washer-image.png">
                    <shortdescription> image showing a washer.</shortdescription>
                 </image>
              <p xml:id="auto_5f9lpfbm">
                 Another application of calculating the area of a part of a circle is designing a metal washer.
                 A washer is a thin, flat ring used to distribute the load of a threaded fastener, such as a bolt or nut.
                 The area of the washer can be calculated using the formula for the area of an annulus, 
                 which helps in determining the amount of material needed to make the washer and its strength.
              </p>
              <example xml:id="auto_a8mmgoxg">
                <statement>
                       <p xml:id="auto_x1p4elam">
                         A metal washer has an outer radius of <m>5</m> cm and an inner radius of <m>2</m> cm. Calculate the area of the washer.
                      </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ka5yu44s">
                         To calculate the area of the washer, we can use the formula for the area of an annulus:
                         <md>
                             <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
                             <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
                             <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow>
                         </md>
                         where <m>R</m> is the outer radius and <m>r</m> is the inner radius.
                         Given that the outer radius is <m>R = 5</m> cm and the inner radius is <m>r = 2</m> cm, we can substitute these values into the formula:
                        <md>
                            <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp \pi (5^2 - 2^2) </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp \frac{22}{7} (25 - 4) </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp 21\frac{22}{7} </mrow>
                            <mrow> = \amp 66 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                        </md>
                        Therefore, the area of the washer is <m>21\text{cm}^2</m>
                    </p>
                </solution>
              </example>
                
    </paragraphs>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Modelling overlapping signal ranges of tower</title>
                    <image source="tower-image.jpg">
                        <shortdescription> image showing towers with overlapping signal ranges.</shortdescription>
                    </image>
                   <p xml:id="auto_f0na5t7g">
                     Another application of calculating the area of a part of a circle is modelling overlapping signal ranges of towers.
                     When two or more towers are located close to each other, their signal ranges may overlap, creating an area where the signals from both towers can be received.
                     The area of this overlap can be calculated using the formula for the area of a segment of a circle, which helps in determining the strength and coverage of the signals in that area.
                  </p>
                <example xml:id="auto_8d7c2ov5">
                    <statement>
                          <p xml:id="auto_xq0vy6l2">
                             Two towers have signal ranges that overlap. The radius of the signal range of the first tower is <m>10</m> km 
                             and the radius of the signal range of the second tower is <m>8</m> km. The central angle of the overlapping area is <m>60^\circ</m>. 
                             Calculate the area of the overlapping signal range.
                          </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                          <p xml:id="auto_pta44fi0">
                              To calculate the area of the overlapping signal range, we can use the formula for the area of a segment of a circle:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{segment} = \amp A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle} </mrow>
                              </md>
                             where <m>A_\text{sector}</m> is the area of the sector formed by the central angle and <m>A_\text{triangle}</m> is the area of the triangle formed by the two radii and the chord of the segment.
                             The area of the sector can be calculated using the formula:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2 </mrow>
                             </md>
                             where <m>\theta</m> is the central angle and <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle.
                             Substituting the given values, we get:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{60}{360} \times \pi (10)^2 </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{6} \times \pi (100) </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 16.67\pi </mrow>
                             </md>
                             The area of the triangle can be calculated using the formula:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2} r^2 \sin(\theta) </mrow>
                             </md>
                             Substituting the given values, we get:
                             <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2} (10)^2 \sin(60^\circ) </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 50 \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 25\sqrt{3} </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = 43.30\text{km}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Finally, we can calculate the area of the segment by subtracting the area of the triangle from the area of the sector:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{segment} = \amp A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle} </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 16.67\pi - 25\sqrt{3} </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 52.36 - 43.30 </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 9.06 \text{km}^2 </mrow>
                             </md>
                             Therefore, the area of the overlapping signal range is <m>9.06 \text{km}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                </example>
            </paragraphs>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_wkmq5t42">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_zjjn94yw">
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_vcto5gnx">
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_nbxjyoaq">
                    Individual work
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_877qghse">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3mo9j1ze">
                    Distribute the exit ticket questions. Learners work individually and silently. Collect responses at the end to inform future instruction.
                </p>
            </li>
            <!-- <li xml:id="auto_cs6ql1kl">
                <title>Exit Ticket Answer Key</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_x349gzpo">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5a90y1ol"><p xml:id="auto_i5v1i3ms">Cake slice: <m>\theta = \frac{360°}{12} = 30°</m>. <m>A = \frac{30}{360} \times \pi(15)^2 = \frac{1}{12} \times 706.86 \approx 58.91\,\text{cm}^2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_q0t8fj21"><p xml:id="auto_yz5mvfzp">Metal ring: <m>A = \pi(8^2 - 5^2) = \pi(39) = \frac{22}{7} \times 39 \approx 122.57\,\text{cm}^2</m></p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_04kcs9p4"><p xml:id="auto_l89surca">Sector: pie-shaped region bounded by two radii and an arc (e.g. pizza slice). Annulus: ring-shaped region between two concentric circles (e.g. washer). Segment: region bounded by a chord and an arc (e.g. signal overlap).</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li> -->
        </dl>
    </axiom>

              <exercises xml:id="exercises-">
                <exercise xml:id="auto_nap2ep4z">
                    <statement>
                        <p xml:id="auto_1rbg1z2o">
                            A circular garden has a radius of <m>10</m> meters. A circular path with a width of <m>2</m> meters surrounds the garden. Calculate the area of the path.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p xml:id="auto_q2jlr2rf">
                            To calculate the area of the path, we can use the formula for the area of an annulus:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow>
                            </md>
                            where <m>R</m> is the outer radius and <m>r</m> is the inner radius.
                            The inner radius of the garden is given as <m>r = 10</m> meters, and the width of the path is <m>2</m> meters, so the outer radius is <m>R = 10 + 2 = 12</m> meters.
                            Substituting these values into the formula, we get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp \pi (12^2 - 10^2) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{22}{7} (144 - 100) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 138.29 \text{m}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore, the area of the path is <m> 138.29 \text{m}^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
                <exercise xml:id="auto_05pjop1z">
                    <statement>
                          <p xml:id="auto_f59umty3">
                             A circular swimming pool has a radius of <m>8</m> meters. A circular deck with a width of <m>3</m> meters surrounds the pool.
                             Calculate the area of the deck.
                          </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ouxv78bd">
                            To calculate the area of the deck, we can use the formula for the area of an annulus:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow>
                            </md>
                            where <m>R</m> is the outer radius and <m>r</m> is the inner radius.
                            The inner radius of the pool is given as <m>r = 8</m> meters, and the width of the deck is <m>3</m> meters, so the outer radius is <m>R = 8 + 3 = 11</m> meters.
                            Substituting these values into the formula, we get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp \pi (11^2 - 8^2) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \pi (121 - 64) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 57 \times \ \frac{22}{7} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 179.14 \text{m}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore, the area of the deck is <m> 179.14 \text{m}^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
                <exercise xml:id="auto_i6ni35wl">
                    <statement>
                          <p xml:id="auto_iirv19hs">
                             A pizza has a radius of <m>14</m> inches and is sliced into 10 equal pieces. 
                             Calculate the area of each slice of pizza.
                          </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p xml:id="auto_28rf57fl">
                            To calculate the area of each slice of pizza, we can use the formula for the area of a sector:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            where <m>\theta</m> is the central angle of the sector and <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle.
                            Since the pizza is sliced into 10 equal pieces, each slice corresponds to a central angle of <m>\theta = \frac{360}{10} = 36^\circ</m>.
                            The radius of the pizza is given as <m>r = 14</m> inches.
                            Substituting these values into the formula, we get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{36}{360} \times \ \frac{22}{7} (14)^2 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{10} \times \ \frac{22}{7} (196) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 61.6 \text{in}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            Therefore, the area of each slice of pizza is <m>61.6 \text{in}^2</m>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
                <exercise xml:id="auto_3zko4ktq">
                    <statement>
                          <p xml:id="auto_zlwyork1">
                             A washer has an outer radius of <m>6</m> cm and an inner radius of <m>3</m> cm. 
                              Calculate the area of the washer.
                          </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                               <p xml:id="auto_ehjmkie9">
                                 To calculate the area of the washer, we can use the formula for the area of an annulus:
                             <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp A_\text{outer circle} - A_\text{inner circle} </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp \pi R^2 - \pi r^2 </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp \pi (R^2 - r^2) </mrow>
                             </md>
                              where <m>R</m> is the outer radius and <m>r</m> is the inner radius.
                              Given that the outer radius is <m>R = 6</m> cm and the inner radius is <m>r = 3</m> cm, we can substitute these values into the formula:
                             <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{annulus} = \amp \frac{22}{7} (6^2 - 3^2) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \ \frac{22}{7} (36 - 9) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 84.85 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                             </md>
                             Therefore, the area of the washer is <m>84.85 \text{cm}^2</m>.
                          </p>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
                <exercise xml:id="auto_dumhs0hq">
                    <statement>
                          <p xml:id="auto_gy3oka8y">
                             An architect is designing a window that is in the shape of a segment of a circle. 
                             The radius of the circle is <m>5</m> meters and the central angle of the segment is <m>60^\circ</m>. Calculate the area of the window.
                          </p>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <p xml:id="auto_77muv2vv">
                            To calculate the area of the window, we can use the formula for the area of a segment of a circle:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{segment} = \amp A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            where <m>A_\text{sector}</m> is the area of the sector formed by the central angle and <m>A_\text{triangle}</m> is the area of the triangle formed by the two radii and the chord of the segment.
                            The area of the sector can be calculated using the formula:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2 </mrow>
                             </md>
                             where <m>\theta</m> is the central angle and <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle.
                             Substituting the given values, we get:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{sector} = \amp \frac{60}{360} \times \pi (5)^2 </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{6} \times \frac{22}{7} (25) </mrow>
                                 <mrow> = \amp 13.09 \text{m}^2 </mrow>
                             </md>
                             The area of the triangle can be calculated using the formula:
                              <md>
                                 <mrow> A_\text{triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2} r^2 \sin(\theta) </mrow>
                             </md>
                            Substituting the given values, we get:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2} (5)^2 \sin(60^\circ) </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} (25) \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \frac{25\sqrt{3}}{4} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp 10.83 \text{m}^2</mrow>
                            </md>
                            Finally, we can calculate the area of the segment by subtracting the area of the triangle from the area of the sector:
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A_\text{segment} = \amp A_\text{sector} - A_\text{triangle} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \ 13.09 - \frac{25\sqrt{3}}{4} </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp \ 13.09 - 10.83 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \amp 2.26 \text{m}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
              </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_p1o93wy9">
                <title>For Struggling Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3uhddfx8">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o16ffi4y"><p xml:id="auto_o8t21459">Provide formula reference cards with visual diagrams.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_37c2n80f"><p xml:id="auto_6hnjeigh">Use physical models (pizza slices, washers, orange slices).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_g8p9u3dd"><p xml:id="auto_p4xbarg6">Break calculations into explicit steps.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5buztfxn"><p xml:id="auto_4qaqbmxa">Focus on one shape type (sector) initially before introducing others.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_vcv4tzyx"><p xml:id="auto_uxmrfojb">Provide worked example templates to follow.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_85kpk4nu">
                <title>For On-Level Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_2fvjhmqs">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_y4rss3p9"><p xml:id="auto_pb4ubfjo">Encourage learners to explain the difference between sector, annulus, and segment.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_rthxcz5h"><p xml:id="auto_8lh4t22z">Provide mixed practice with all three shape types.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_dnxazilr"><p xml:id="auto_e73pnka0">Challenge learners to identify the correct shape in word problems.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_ln0oudym"><p xml:id="auto_gk5yqy0s">Ask learners to create their own real-life problems.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_bvsb1b40">
                <title>For Advanced Learners</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_vbjn34ju">
                    <ul>
                        <li xml:id="auto_zyojfssi"><p xml:id="auto_h7cpmiv4">Challenge with annular sectors (combination of annulus and sector).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4dfp25am"><p xml:id="auto_8qzanbbl">Explore optimisation problems (maximise area with constraints).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_15xea5vl"><p xml:id="auto_ndr0k5j7">Connect to careers (engineering, architecture, telecommunications).</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_kel4k38x"><p xml:id="auto_bhr8dgms">Investigate common regions between overlapping circles.</p></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_a2v7n42e"><p xml:id="auto_79wqvcar">Derive formulas from first principles.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

